Doc correction for limit param

New 'limit=' support for SplunkDF

You can now specify the 'limit=' paramater to SplunkDF.search() or 
SplunkDF.search_df() to limit the number of search results retrieved, 
which will probably make the query complete more quickly too.  

One important note is that without 'limit', SplunkDF will use an 
'export' search, which returns ALL search results.  But 'export' 
searches don't support the 'count' paramter, which underlies 'limit'.  
If you supply a 'limit', SplunkDF will instead use a 'oneshot' search.  
The limit will be honored, but is also subject to a server side max 
(default 50,000 if it's not overridden in limits.conf).  So if you want 
to use limit, don't limit to anything more than 50000.

Support for `fields` arg and fixed deprecated json normalization method.

Splunk's default behavior seems to have changed since this module was written.  In particular, you no
longer get all the fields in the search results by default, only those you specifically search on or those you ask for in a '| fields=' stanza.  For a quick workaround, SplunkDF.search() and .search_df()
now allow you to specified the 'fields' argument, which is a comma-separated list of fields you want.
By default, we use '*' for this arg, which means all fields.  It's literally adding '| fields=*'
to the end of each query by default.  If for some reason this doesn't work well for you, you can
set 'fields=None' when you call the search functions and it won't modify the query at all.

Also, the old pandas way of normalizing JSON data (pd.io.json.json_normalize) has been replaced with
the newer pd.json_normalize() function.

New huntlib.data module provides multi-file capable read_csv() and read_json()

The new huntlib.data module provides convenience functions to make it easier to deal with data
files.  The first two functions are wildcard-capable replacements for pandas' read_csv() and
read_json() functions.  The new versions operate identically and accept all the same parameters
(they're just passed through to the underlying pandas functions) but the filename can contain
wildcards for reading multiple files.

Ditch the Splunk oneshot() API

The Splunk oneshot() API was super slow (seemingly CPU bound). Removed
it entirely and now use Splunk's Jobs API to retrieve results when the
'limit' paramter is specified. Further, we always use multiprocessing
in these cases, even if just with the default worker count of 1.
Limit searches are *much* faster now. Searches with no limit
specified still use the Splunk export() API, which is slower, but
ensures that all results are retrieved.

Smarter arg handling for search/search_df and unified results handling for all search types.

The search() and search_df() functions now use 'args' and 'kwargs' to handle their args, which
makes it MUCH easier to pass the searches through.  Changes to the search() code also to provide
basic sanity checking on the args, including enforcing the previous default values.

Both parallel and export() searches now use common code to process their results.  This was not
previously the case, leading to bad things like Splunk messages not being handled consistently,
internal fields not being filtered correctly, etc.

Added new script to control test infrastructure (Splunk & Elastic)

* Added 'test-infra.sh' script to start/stop the docker containers and load the data needed to
  run the unit tests. This makes it easier (and faster) to perform tests during development, since
  you can leave the test infra running and just execute the tests and save a few minutes during

  directly.

Added data chunk post-processing to read_json()/read_csv()

* Changed _read_multi's 'func' parameter to be 'read_function' since we now have both read and
  post-processing function parameters.
* Added a new 'post_function' parameter to read_csv, read_json and the backend _read_multi
  functions.  As each individual file is read, _read_multi can optionally call a post-processing
  function to manipulate the data before it's added to the resulting DataFrame. As a beneficial
  side effect, the new mechanism for reading multiple files appends each chunk as it's read, rather
  than keeping them all in memory until the end.  This should make things faster and use less memory.
* Added documentation about the new post-processing function
